{{Christianity |width=24em<!--should match infobox above--> |state=collapsed}}

'''The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints''', often informally known as the '''LDS Church''' or '''Mormon Church''', is a [[Nontrinitarianism|nontrinitarian]], [[Christianity|Christian]] [[Restorationism|restorationist]] church that considers itself to be the [[Restoration (Latter Day Saints)|restoration]] of the [[One true church#Latter Day Saint movement|original church]] founded by [[Jesus in Christianity|Jesus Christ]]. The church is headquartered in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]], in the United States, and has established congregations and built [[Temple (LDS Church)|temples]] worldwide. According to the church, it has over 16 million [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints membership statistics|members]] and 65,000 [[Missionary (LDS Church)|full-time volunteer missionaries]].<ref name="Statistics 2018"<ref name="Statistics 2018">{{cite news|title=2017 Statistical Report for 2018 April Conference|url=https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/article/2017-statistical-report-april-2018-general-conference|publisher=Intellectual Reserve, Inc.|website=MormonNewsroom.org|date=March 31, 2018|accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2012, the [[National Council of Churches]] ranked the church as the fourth-largest [[Christian denomination]] in the United States,<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.ncccusa.org/news/120209yearbook2012.html |title= National Council of Churches News: Church giving drops $1.2 billion reports 2012 Yearbook of Churches |date= March 20, 2012 |work= ncccusa.org |publisher= [[National Council of Churches]]}}</ref> with over 6.5 million members there as of January 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=LDS Statistics and Church Facts {{!}} Total Church Membership|url=https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/facts-and-statistics/country/united-states|publisher=Intellectual Reserve, Inc.|website=MormonNewsroom.org|accessdate=September 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref> It is the [[List of denominations in the Latter Day Saint movement|largest denomination]] in the [[Latter Day Saint movement]] founded by [[Joseph Smith]] during the early 19th century period of religious revival known as the [[Second Great Awakening]].

Adherents, often referred to as "Latter-day Saints" or, less formally, "[[Mormons]]", view faith in Jesus Christ and his [[Substitutionary atonement|atonement]] as fundamental principles of their religion.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1976|p= 121}} "The fundamental principles of our religion are the testimony of the Apostles and Prophets, concerning Jesus Christ, that He died, was buried, and rose again the third day, and ascended into heaven; and all other things which pertain to our religion are only appendages to it."</ref><ref>{{citation |authorlink= Thomas S. Monson |first= Thomas S. |last= Monson |url= http://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/ensign/2003/01/the-way-of-the-master |title= The Way of the Master |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= January 2003 |pages= 2–7}}</ref> Church theology includes the Christian doctrine of [[Salvation (Christianity)|salvation]] only through Jesus Christ,<ref name="ReferenceA">"For salvation cometh to none such except it be through repentance and faith on the Lord Jesus Christ." Book of Mormon, {{lds|Mosiah|mosiah|3|12}}</ref> though LDS doctrines regarding the [[God in Mormonism|nature of God]] and the [[Exaltation (Mormonism)|potential of mankind]] differ significantly from mainstream Christianity. The church has an [[biblical canon|open canon]] which includes four [[religious text|scriptural texts]]:<ref>{{lds|Articles of Faith|a_of_f|1|8}}</ref> the Bible (both [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]]s), the [[Book of Mormon]], the [[Doctrine and Covenants]], and the [[Pearl of Great Price (Mormonism)|Pearl of Great Price]]. Other than the Bible, the majority of the LDS canon constitutes revelation received by Joseph Smith and recorded by his scribes which includes commentary and [[exegesis]] about the Bible, texts described as [[apocryphal|lost parts of the Bible]], and other works believed to be written by ancient [[prophet]]s. Because of some of the doctrinal differences, [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]], and several [[Protestant]] churches consider the church to be distinct and [[Mormonism and Christianity|separate from mainstream Christianity]].<ref name="kennedy2004">{{Citation|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2004/february/14.18.html |title=Winning them softly|first=John W.|last=Kennedy|date=February 2004|volume=48|issue=2|work=Christianity Today|accessdate=October 7, 2006}}</ref>

Under the doctrine of [[continuous revelation|continuing]] [[revelation (Latter Day Saints)|revelation]], Latter-day Saints believe that the church [[President of the Church (LDS Church)|president]] is a modern-day "[[prophet, seer, and revelator]]" and that Jesus Christ, under the direction of [[God the Father]], leads the church by revealing his will to its president. <!--replace when new president is chosen--> Individual members of the church believe that they can also receive personal revelation from God in conducting their lives.<ref>{{citation |quote= Perhaps the puzzle some feel can be explained by the reality that each of us has two different channels to God. We have a channel of governance through our prophet and other leaders. This channel, which has to do with doctrine, ordinances, and commandments, results in obedience. We also have a channel of personal testimony, which is direct to God. This has to do with His existence, our relationship to Him, and the truth of His restored gospel. This channel results in knowledge. |authorlink= Dallin H. Oaks |first= Dallin H. |last= Oaks |date= May 2008 |url= http://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/ensign/2008/05/testimony |title= Testimony |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]}}</ref> The president heads a hierarchical structure with various levels reaching down to local congregations. [[Bishop (Latter Day Saints)|Bishops]], drawn from the [[laity]], lead local congregations. Male members, beginning in January of the year they reach age 12,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/church/news/age-changes-for-youth-progression-and-ordination-announced?lang=eng|title=Age Changes for Youth Progression and Ordination Announced - Church News and Events|website=www.churchofjesuschrist.org|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>[https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/multimedia/file/age-group-announcement-january-2019.pdf Age Group Announcment, January 2019]</ref> may be ordained to the [[Priesthood (LDS Church)|priesthood]], provided they are living the standards of the church. Women are not ordained to the priesthood but do occupy leadership roles in some church [[auxiliary organization (LDS Church)|organizations]].<ref name="ballard2007">{{Citation |last= Ballard |first= M. Russell |authorlink= M. Russell Ballard |title = Faith, Family, Facts, and Fruits |url= http://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/ensign/2007/11/faith-family-facts-and-fruits |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= November 2007}}</ref>

Both men and women may serve as missionaries and the church maintains a large missionary program that [[proselytism|proselytizes]] and conducts [[LDS Humanitarian Services|humanitarian services]] worldwide. Faithful members adhere to church laws of [[Law of chastity|sexual purity]], [[Word of Wisdom|health]], [[Fasting#Mormonism|fasting]], and [[Sabbath in Christianity#The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Sabbath observance]], and contribute ten percent of their income to the church in [[Tithing (Latter Day Saints)|tithing]]. The church also teaches about sacred [[Ordinance (Latter Day Saints)|ordinances]] through which adherents make [[Covenant (Latter Day Saints)|covenants]] with God, including [[Baptism (Mormonism)|baptism]], [[Confirmation (Latter Day Saints)|confirmation]], the [[Sacrament (LDS Church)|sacrament]] ([[Eucharist|holy communion]]), [[Priesthood (LDS Church)|priesthood ordination]], [[Endowment (Latter Day Saints)|endowment]], and [[celestial marriage]] (marriage blessings which extend beyond mortality)—all of which are of great significance to church members.<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/liahona/2001/11/ordinances-and-covenants |title= Ordinances and Covenants |last= Neuenschwander |first= Dennis B. |journal= [[Liahona (magazine)|Liahona]] |date= November 2001}}</ref>

==History==
{{Main|History of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints}}
The history of the LDS Church is typically divided into three broad time periods: (1) the early history during the lifetime of [[Joseph Smith]], which is in common with all Latter Day Saint movement churches; (2) a pioneer era under the leadership of [[Brigham Young]] and his 19th-century successors; and (3) a modern era beginning around the turn of the 20th century as [[Utah]] achieved statehood.

===Beginnings===
[[File:Joseph Smith first vision stained glass.jpg|upright|thumb|Adherents believe that [[Joseph Smith]] was called to be a modern-day prophet through, among other events, a [[First Vision|visitation]] from [[God the Father]] and [[Jesus|Jesus Christ]].]]
{{See also|History of the Latter Day Saint movement|Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)}}
The LDS Church, originally called the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Christ]], was formally organized by [[Joseph Smith]] on April 6, 1830, in [[burned-over district|western New York]].<ref>Scholars and eyewitnesses disagree whether the church was organized in [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester, New York]] at the Smith log home, or in [[Fayette, New York|Fayette]] at the home of [[Peter Whitmer]]. {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|p=109}}; {{Harvnb|Marquardt|2005|pp=223–23}} (arguing that organization in Manchester is most consistent with eye-witness statements). The LDS Church officially favors organization in Fayette.{{Citation |last= Lloyd |first= R. Scott |title= 'Major discovery' discussed at Mormon History Association Conference |periodical= LDS Church News |publisher= LDS Church |date= May 22, 2009 |url= https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2009-05-22/major-discovery-discussed-at-mormon-history-association-conference-33828 |accessdate= September 23, 2014}}</ref> Smith later changed the name to the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints after he stated he had received a revelation to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/115?lang=eng|title=Doctrine and Covenants 115:4|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Initial converts were drawn to the church in part because of the newly published [[Book of Mormon]], a self-described chronicle of [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous American]] prophets that Smith said he had translated from [[golden plates]].<ref>Book of Mormon, [//www.churchofjesuschrist.org/scriptures/bofm/introduction "Introduction"].</ref>

Smith intended to establish the [[New Jerusalem]] in North America, called ''[[Zion (Latter Day Saints)|Zion]]''.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|p=122}}; LDS {{lds|D&C|dc|57|1|3}}: "the city New Jerusalem shall be built by the gathering of the saints, beginning at [Jackson County, Missouri], even the place of the temple, which temple shall be reared in this generation".</ref> In 1831, the church moved to [[Kirtland, Ohio]] (the eastern boundary of Zion),<ref>{{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|p=97}} (citing letter by Smith to Kirtland converts, quoted in {{Harvnb|Howe|1833|p=111}}). In 1834, Smith designated Kirtland as one of the "[[Stake (Latter Day Saints)|stakes]]" of Zion, referring to the tent–stakes metaphor of [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] {{lds||isa|54|2}}.</ref> and began establishing an outpost in [[Jackson County, Missouri]] (Zion's "center place"),<ref>{{Harvnb|Smith|Cowdery|Rigdon|Williams|1835|p=154}}; {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|p=162}}; {{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|p=109}}.</ref> where he planned to eventually move the church headquarters.<ref>Smith said in 1831 that God intended the Mormons to "retain a strong hold in the land of Kirtland, for the space of five years". ([[Doctrine and Covenants]] {{lds||dc|64|21}}).</ref> However, in 1833, Missouri settlers brutally expelled the Latter Day Saints from Jackson County,<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=222–27}}; {{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|p=137}} (noting that the brutality of the Jackson Countians aroused sympathy for the Mormons and was almost universally deplored by the media).</ref> and the church was unable via a [[Zion's Camp|paramilitary expedition]] to recover the land.<ref>{{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|pp=141, 146–59}}; {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|p=322}}.</ref> Nevertheless, the church flourished in Kirtland as Smith published new revelations and the church built the [[Kirtland Temple]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|p=101}}; {{Harvnb|Arrington|1992|p=21}} (by summer of 1835, there were 1500 to 2000 Saints in Kirtland); ''Desert Morning News 2008 Church Almanac'' p. 655 (from 1831 to 1838, church membership grew from 680 to 17,881).</ref> culminating in a dedication of the building similar to the day of [[Pentecost]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=310–19}}; {{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|p=178}}.</ref> The Kirtland era ended in 1838, after a [[Kirtland Safety Society|financial scandal]] rocked the church and caused widespread defections.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=328–38}}; {{Harvnb|Brooke|1994|p=221}} ("Ultimately, the rituals and visions dedicating the Kirtland temple were not sufficient to hold the church together in the face of a mounting series of internal disputes.")</ref> Smith regrouped with the remaining church in [[Far West, Missouri]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1905|p=24}} (referring to the Far West church as the "church in Zion"); {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|p=345}} (The revelation calling Far West "Zion" had the effect of "implying that Far West was to take the place of Independence".)</ref> but tensions soon escalated into [[Mormon War (1838)|violent conflicts]] with the old Missouri settlers.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=357–364}}; {{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|pp=227–30}}; {{Harvnb|Remini|2002|p=134}}; {{Harvnb|Quinn|1994|pp=97–98}}.</ref> Believing the Saints to be in insurrection, the [[Lilburn Boggs|Missouri governor]] ordered that the Saints be [[Missouri Executive Order 44|"exterminated or driven from the State]]."<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|p=367}} (Boggs' executive order stated that the Mormon community had "made war upon the people of this State" and that "the Mormons must be treated as enemies, and must be exterminated or driven from the State if necessary for the public peace"). In 1976, [[Missouri]] issued a formal apology for this unconstitutional order {{Harv|Bushman|2005|p=398}}.</ref> In 1839, the Saints converted a swampland on the banks of the [[Mississippi River]] into [[Nauvoo, Illinois]], which became the church's new headquarters.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=383–84}}.</ref>

Nauvoo grew rapidly as [[Mormon missionary|missionaries]] sent to Europe and elsewhere gained new converts who then flooded into Nauvoo.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|p=409}}; {{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|pp=258, 264–65}}.</ref> Meanwhile, Smith introduced [[polygamy]] to his closest associates.<ref>{{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|pp=334–36}}; {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=437, 644}}.</ref> He also established [[Sealing (Mormonism)|ceremonies]], which he stated the Lord had revealed to him, to allow righteous people to [[Exaltation (Mormonism)|become gods]] (joint heirs with Christ, see [[Divinization (Christian)|theosis]])<ref>LDS {{lds|D&C|dc|132|18|20}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |url= http://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/ensign/1975/10/the-lords-plan-for-men-and-women |title= The Lord's Plan for Men and Women |date= October 1975 |first= Spencer W. |last= Kimball |authorlink= Spencer W. Kimball |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]}}</ref> in the afterlife,<ref>{{Harvnb|Widmer|2000|p=119}} (Smith echoed the words of Paul that faithful saints may become co-heirs with Jesus Romans 8:17); {{Harvnb|Roberts|1909|pp=502–03}}; {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=497–98}} (the [[second anointing]] provided a conditional guarantee that those persons who were pure and faithful would be exalted, even if they sinned, if they were sealed by the Holy Spirit of promise).</ref> and a [[Council of Fifty|secular institution]] to govern the [[Millennium|Millennial]] kingdom.<ref>{{Harvnb|Quinn|1994|pp=120–22}}; {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=519–21}} (describing the Council of Fifty noting that Smith prophesied "the entire overthrow of this nation in a few years", at which time the Kingdom of God would be prepared to lead)</ref> He also introduced the church to a full accounting of his [[First Vision]], in which two heavenly "personages" ([[God the Father]] and his Son, [[Jesus Christ]]) appeared to him at age 14. This vision would come to be regarded by the LDS Church as the most important event in human history since the [[resurrection of Jesus]].<ref>{{Citation |publisher= LDS Church |title= Mission of the Prophet Joseph Smith {{ndash}} First Vision: This Is My Beloved Son. Hear Him! |url= http://josephsmith.net/article/the-first-vision?lang=eng |work= JosephSmith.net |accessdate= September 23, 2014}}; {{Harvnb|Allen|1966|p=29}} (belief in the First Vision now considered second in importance only to belief in the divinity of Jesus.); {{Citation |title= What Are People Asking about Us? |last= Hinckley |first= Gordon B. |authorlink= Gordon B. Hinckley |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= November 1998 |url= http://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/ensign/1998/11/what-are-people-asking-about-us |quote= [N]othing we teach, nothing we live by is of greater importance than this initial declaration.}}</ref> Church members believe Joseph Smith is the first modern-day prophet.<ref name=Lyon2013>{{cite journal|last1=Lyon|first1=Stephanie J.|title=Psychotherapy and the Mormon Faith|journal=Journal of Religion and Health|volume=52|issue=2|year=2013|pages=622–630|issn=0022-4197|doi=10.1007/s10943-013-9677-2|pmid=23337975}}</ref>

On June 27, 1844, Smith and his brother [[Hyrum Smith|Hyrum]] were [[Death of Joseph Smith|murdered by a mob]] in [[Carthage, Illinois]],<ref>''Encyclopedia of Latter-Day Saint History'' p. 824; {{Harvnb|Brodie|1971|pp=393–94}}; {{Harvnb|Bushman|2005}}.</ref> while being held on charges of treason.<ref>Many local Illinoisans were uneasy with Mormon power, and their unease was fanned by the local media after Smith suppressed a newspaper containing an exposé regarding plural marriage, theocracy, and other sensitive and oft-misinterpreted issues. The suppression resulted in Smith being arrested, tried, and acquitted for "inciting a riot". On June 25, Joseph let himself be arrested and tried for the riot charges again, this time in Carthage, the county seat, where he was incarcerated without bail on a new charge of treason. {{citation |contribution-url= http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/EoM/id/4208 |contribution= Smith, Joseph: Legal Trials of Joseph Smith |first= Joseph I. |last= Bentley |pages= 1346–1348 |editor1-last= Ludlow |editor1-first= Daniel H |editor1-link= Daniel H. Ludlow |title= [[Encyclopedia of Mormonism]] |location= New York |publisher= [[Macmillan Publishing]] |year= 1992 |isbn= 0-02-879602-0 |oclc= 24502140}}</ref> Because Hyrum was Joseph's designated successor,<ref>{{citation |title=none|quote= Did Joseph Smith ordain any man to take his place. He did. Who was it? It was Hyrum, but Hyrum fell a martyr before Joseph did. If Hyrum had lived he would have acted for Joseph. |first= Brigham |last= Young |newspaper= [[Times and Seasons]] |volume= 5 |date= October 15, 1844 |page= 683}}</ref> their deaths caused a [[Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)|succession crisis]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Quinn|1994|p=143}}; {{Harvtxt|Brodie|1971|p=398}}.</ref> and [[Brigham Young]] assumed leadership over the majority of Saints.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bushman|2005|pp=556–57}}.</ref> Young had been a close associate of Smith's and was the senior [[Apostle (Latter Day Saints)|apostle]] of the [[Quorum of the Twelve]].<ref>Smith's position as Prophet and [[President of the Church]] was originally left vacant, but later filled when the apostles could regroup based on the restored principle that the most senior apostle would always be the next President of the Church. As a result, Young, and any other senior [[Apostle (Latter Day Saints)|apostle]] of the [[Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|Quorum of the Twelve]], would be ordained [[President of the Church (LDS Church)|President of the Church]] as a matter of course upon the death of the former President, subject to unanimous agreement of the Quorum of the Twelve.</ref> Other splinter groups followed other leaders in their own interpretation of the Latter Day Saint movement.  These groups have no affiliation with the LDS Church.<ref>{{Harvnb|Quinn|1994|pp=198–211}}.</ref>

===Pioneer era===
[[File:BrighamYoung1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Brigham Young]] led the LDS Church from 1844 until his death in 1877.]]
For two years after Smith's death, conflicts escalated between Mormons and other Illinois residents. Smith had predicted that the church would go to the West and be established in the tops of the Rocky Mountains.<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.jefflindsay.com/LDSFAQ/FQ_prophecies.shtml#rockies |title= LDS FAQ: The Saints to Flourish in the Rocky Mountains |last= Lindsay |first= Jeff |authorlink= Jeff Lindsay (engineer) |accessdate= September 22, 2014}}</ref> [[Brigham Young]] took Smith's advice and led his followers, known in modern times as the [[Mormon pioneers]], to [[Nebraska]] and then in 1847 to what became the [[Utah Territory]].<ref name="emigration-religious-freedom">{{cite web |url= http://www.nps.gov/mopi/historyculture/index.htm |title= Mormon Pioneer National Historic Trail: History & Culture |website= nps.gov |publisher= [[U.S. National Park Service]] |quote= The great Mormon migration of 1846–1847 was but one step in the LDS' quest for religious freedom and growth. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141208215457/http://www.nps.gov/mopi/historyculture/index.htm |archive-date= December 8, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> As groups (over 60,000) arrived over a period of years, LDS settlers branched out and colonized a large region now known as the [[Mormon Corridor]].

Young incorporated the LDS Church as a legal entity, and initially governed both the church and the state as a [[theocracy|theocratic]] leader. He also publicized the practice of [[Mormonism and polygamy|plural marriage]],<ref>The Mormon doctrine of plural wives was officially announced by one of the [[Quorum of the Twelve|Twelve Apostles]] [[Orson Pratt]] and Smith's successor [[Brigham Young]] in a special conference of the elders of the church assembled in the [[Salt Lake Tabernacle]] on August 28, 1852, and reprinted in an extra edition of the ''[[Deseret News]]'' Only a small percentage of church leaders participated in plural marriage believing it was a part of a restitution of ancient Priesthood blessings and a commandment of god to raise up a righteous generation. At the time, it was not barred by statute within the United States.{{Cite news | title = Minutes of conference: a special conference of the elders of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints assembled in the Tabernacle, Great Salt Lake City, August 28th, 1852, 10 o'clock, a.m., pursuant to public notice | work = [[Deseret News|Deseret News Extra]] | date = September 14, 1852 | page = 14}}. See also: [[Origin of Latter Day Saint polygamy#The 1850s: Official sanction in the LDS Church|The 1850s: Official sanction in the LDS Church]]</ref> a form of [[polygamy]].

By 1857, tensions had again escalated between Mormons and other Americans, largely as a result of accusations involving polygamy and the theocratic rule of the Utah Territory by Young.<ref>See Tullidge, Edward, ''History of Salt Lake City'', 132-35 (Original from the University of Michigan, 1886).</ref> The [[Utah War|Utah Mormon War]] ensued from 1857 to 1858, which resulted in the relatively peaceful invasion of Utah by the [[United States Army]],<!--FOOTNOTE--><ref>The most notable instance of violence during this war was the tragic [[Mountain Meadows massacre]], in which leaders of a local Mormon militia, contrary to top church leaders orders, ordered the massacre of a civilian emigrant party who had the misfortune of traveling through Utah during the escalating military tensions. The Mormons feared the mobs which murdered their families at the Haun's mill massacre and other illegal thefts of land, and murders which had plagued them back east.</ref><!--

--> after which Young agreed to step down from power and be replaced by a non-Mormon territorial governor, [[Alfred Cumming (governor)|Alfred Cumming]].<!--

FOOTNOTE--><ref>To combat the notion that rank-and-file Mormons were unhappy under Young's leadership, Cumming noted that he had offered to help any leave the territory who desired. Of the 50,000 inhabitants of the territory of Utah, the underwhelming response—56 men, 33 women, and 71 children, most of whom stated they left for economic reasons—impressed Cumming, as did the fact that Mormon leaders contributed supplies to the emigrants. Cumming to [Secretary of State Lewis Cass], written by Thomas Kane, May 2, 1858, BYU Special Collections.</ref><!--

--> Nevertheless, the LDS Church still wielded significant political power in the Utah Territory.<!--

